3
00:00:41,000 --> 00:02:30,000
TRUE
Lion was filmed on location Ganesh Talai & West Bengal.
4
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:52,000
TRUE-ISH
Lion is definitely based on a true story. Just how closely we're about to find out. The landscape in which Saroo grew up is the same as in this scene, & in the book of his life, Saroo talks about chasing butterflies, if not quite standing amongst them in this fashion. 
5
00:02:52,000 --> 00:03:03,000
TRUE
Saroo & his brother certainly spent time out & about, although not that much, as they had a middle brother, Kallu, who was closer to Guddu in age, & usually Saroo was left at home with his younger sister. 
6
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:30,000
FALSE-ISH
This is never mentioned in the book & it's the kind of thing Saroo would have mentioned, particularly if it had happened on this very special day. Life was hard, however, & they did have to beg & steal as well as doing whatever work they could find in order to eat. 
7
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:04,000
FALSE-ISH
Quite a lot of licence appears to have been taken here but the spirit of the scene is true & although it didn't happen, it's true that it didn't happen in Khandwa in 1986. 
8
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:54,000
TRUE-ISH
Nothing like this is reported as happening on this day, but it's the kind of thing that may have happened in general. 
9
00:04:54,000 --> 00:05:16,000
FALSE
This is a creation of the filmmakers, designed to set up an important flashback for Saroo in 20 years' time. But it didn't happen. 
10
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:47,000
FALSE-ISH
Saroo actually describes what happened on this evening, & there was no illicit milk involved. 
11
00:05:47,000 --> 00:06:26,000
FALSE-ISH
Something similar could have happened at some point but it definitely didn't happen today. 
12
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:41,000
TRUE
Saroo's mum did leave them alone — "perhaps to see if she could get us some more food", writes Saroo — & he was often responsible for his sister's welfare. 
13
00:06:41,000 --> 00:07:12,000
TRUE
On this particular night, Guddu was leaving as he usually did, to go to a neighbouring town where he would look for work & usually sleep there. Unusually, Saroo did ask his brother if he could accompany him on this night. 
14
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:23,000
FALSE-ISH
Rather than argue with Saroo, Guddu "thought about it for a moment & then agreed".
15
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:58,000
FALSE
None of this happened. There was no argument. 
16
00:07:58,000 --> 00:08:13,000
TRUE
Saroo remembered this ride vividly as it was the first time he had accompanied Guddu on such a ride at this time of night. He even recalls Guddu's friend shouting his name, as he felt proud to be out with his brother. 
17
00:08:13,000 --> 00:08:16,000
TRUE
Saroo writes that the train pulled in noisily & they scuttled aboard & made themselves comfortable. 
18
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:29,000
TRUE-ISH
Although this is the kind of thing they will have done, there is no mention of it on this particular occasion in the book.
19
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:49,000
TRUE
They did find an empty carriage & Saroo did fall asleep, but there is no mention of a coin. 
20
00:08:49,000 --> 00:09:30,000
TRUE
Saroo did insist that he couldn't go on without a rest & he did lie down on a bench on the platform. 
21
00:09:30,000 --> 00:10:07,000
TRUE
Guddu did leave him there & did say he would be back, but the jalebis thing is made up, & also Guddu wasn't on his way to lift bales. He spent most of his time in this town. This was a normal night for him. He told Saroo he had to do a few things. 
22
00:10:07,000 --> 00:11:18,000
TRUE
It seems there was a little less exploration & calling out of his brother's name in reality, but Saroo did board the train, figuring it was the one that would take them back home & that Guddu would come back & find him on there. So he got on & went straight to sleep. 
23
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:42,000
TRUE-ISH
The train was not quite deserted in reality, & Saroo didn't call out for his brother. He just got on, found an empty carriage & went back to sleep. 
24
00:11:42,000 --> 00:12:49,000
TRUE
After a second of feeling happy that he might be on his way home, this is exactly what happened. 
25
00:12:49,000 --> 00:13:27,000
TRUE
He kept looking out of the window to see if he recognised anything but became increasingly scared. He writes: "I wept & slept & sometimes looked out of the window."
26
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:41,000
TRUE-ISH
Although there is no mention of this in Saroo's account, it's not unreasonable that something of this nature occurred. 
27
00:13:41,000 --> 00:14:28,000
FALSE-ISH
Although he says the train occasionally stopped & he did shout for help, he also says "somehow no-one ever saw me". 
28
00:14:28,000 --> 00:14:55,000
TRUE-ISH
Saroo never wrote about a storm or an apple core, but he admits his memories of that journey were not great. He was convinced he'd only travelled for 12-15 hours, but in reality, it must've been nearer 30. So even though he was used to hunger, he must have looked for food. 
29
00:14:55,000 --> 00:15:36,000
TRUE
Saroo watched out of the window as the train arrived in Calcutta (as it was then) & hundreds or thousands of people came into view on the platform. 
30
00:15:36,000 --> 00:16:59,000
TRUE-ISH
He did leave the train when the door opened & he did start asking people for his home town, although there is no mention in the book of climbing anything or shouting for his family. 
31
00:16:59,000 --> 00:17:49,000
FALSE
Nah, he never did any of this. What he did was more interesting but less cinematic. For a couple of weeks he tried to catch a train back home, so kept jumping trains to different places & ending up back in Calcutta. Poor little blighter.
32
00:17:49,000 --> 00:18:31,000
TRUE-ISH
More or less true. After a couple of weeks of living in the station & taking trains in the day, he slept close to a bunch of street kids he'd already seen quite a few times. 
33
00:18:31,000 --> 00:19:35,000
FALSE
In reality "the children weren't welcoming" & he writes of one time he slept on "a hard wooden seat close to them". 
34
00:19:35,000 --> 00:19:50,000
TRUE
This scene is pretty much exactly as it is described in the book. 
35
00:19:50,000 --> 00:20:23,000
TRUE-ISH
He ran straight down a platform (which is where they were in reality, rather than in a covered subway) & jumped off the end & onto the tracks. 
36
00:20:23,000 --> 00:20:45,000
FALSE-ISH
There was no gate & no guard. Rather, Saroo ran off down the tracks. 
37
00:20:45,000 --> 00:20:56,000
TRUE-ISH
Having jumped onto the train track, Saroo is almost hit by a train, flattening himself against a wall for a long time, the train being composed of many carriages. Much more exciting than a silly old bus. 
38
00:20:56,000 --> 00:21:49,000
TRUE-ISH
Although it was very different to the one in the film, Saroo did come across a temple at one point. (Not on the night he was chased from the station though.) However, on that night he did come across some sleeping holy men on a riverbank. 
39
00:21:49,000 --> 00:22:26,000
TRUE-ISH
Again, it didn't happen yet & when it did, it happened under a bridge & was on a much smaller scale, with pictures & little statues on wooden planks. (Plus the goddess was on a tiger, not a lion.) But he did eat the fruit. (And took coins.)
40
00:22:26,000 --> 00:22:49,000
TRUE-ISH
On another occasion, he slept close to a shrine under a bridge & when he woke up, there was a holy man meditating. He was later joined by others. So it has the essence of truth. 
41
00:22:49,000 --> 00:23:17,000
TRUE
He actually walked along the river bank for the first time the previous evening, the first night he'd left the station, after a couple of weeks being in Calcutta. & yes, he saw many things. 
42
00:23:17,000 --> 00:23:27,000
FALSE
This whole cardboard thing never happened in real life. 
43
00:23:27,000 --> 00:24:01,000
TRUE
Cardboard aside, Saroo walked the streets for months & would often gravitate towards the tracks as they held for him the possibility of returning home. 
44
00:24:01,000 --> 00:24:50,000
TRUE-ISH
One time Saroo was sitting on the railways tracks, a railway worker approached him & was kind to him. 
45
00:24:50,000 --> 00:25:11,000
FALSE-ISH
This is a fictionalised version of what happened with the railway worker, but it's very far removed from the reality. He was actually taken to a shack next to the tracks. No kite.
46
00:25:11,000 --> 00:25:46,000
FALSE-ISH
Saroo actually stayed for three nights with the railway worker & his fellow workers in a shack made of corrugated iron & cardboard. There is no mention of dinner-time conversation however. 
47
00:25:46,000 --> 00:26:30,000
FALSE
The reality of this meeting was a lot less glamorous. It wasn't set in an apartment & it didn't include anything as luxurious as fizzy orange. 
48
00:26:30,000 --> 00:26:45,000
FALSE 
There was no Noor. 
49
00:26:45,000 --> 00:27:28,000
TRUE-ISH
The railway man on whom Noor is based promised Saroo on his second day with him that he'd arranged for a man to visit & that this man would be able to help him. 
50
00:27:28,000 --> 00:29:17,000
TRUE
The details are all wrong but the thrust is right. A man came & lay down with Saroo making lots of promises. Saroo played along but intuited that the man was bad news. 
51
00:29:17,000 --> 00:29:36,000
FALSE-ISH
None of this is real. The relationship between Noor (who didn't exist) & Rama (who kind of did) didn't exist. 
52
00:29:36,000 --> 00:30:22,000
FALSE 
None of this happened. All of this scene is totally made up. 
53
00:30:22,000 --> 00:30:39,000
TRUE-ISH
Again, the details are invented, but something similar did happen. On his third night in the railway worker's shack, awaiting the return of the creepy man, Saroo made a run for it. 
54
00:30:39,000 --> 00:30:53,000
TRUE-ISH
Saroo was chased by a couple of the railways workers & he hid in a sewerage pipe to get away from them. 
55
00:30:53,000 --> 00:32:39,000
TRUE
Enough of this scene is true to mark it true. Saroo's mother did move rocks for a living, he almost certainly helped her at some stage, & he must have thought constantly about his mother as he slept rough in Calcutta. 
56
00:32:39,000 --> 00:32:57,000
TRUE
Although he doesn't say exactly how long he was on the streets (probably because he doesn't know), a couple of months seems reasonable. 
57
00:32:57,000 --> 00:33:06,000
FALSE-ISH
There is no mention of any of this in the book.  Though it is likely Saroo foraged extensively for food & valuables.
58
00:33:06,000 --> 00:33:13,000
FALSE
A reference to the butterflies in the opening scene maybe, but a made-up one. 
59
00:33:13,000 --> 00:33:24,000
FALSE
The spoon thing appears in an early version of the script, but unfortunately, in real life, it never really happened. 
60
00:33:24,000 --> 00:33:34,000
FALSE-ISH
Saroo saw lots of dead bodies during his time in Calcutta, which was very much more harrowing than is portrayed in the film, but he never writes about seeing a funeral. 
61
00:33:34,000 --> 00:33:51,000
FALSE
All of this stuff with the spoon is a way of enlivening a very simple meeting with the teenage boy who ends up taking Saroo to the police station. 
62
00:33:51,000 --> 00:34:40,000
FALSE
This is a lovely little scene, but completely invented. He met the boy who took him to the police in the street. The boy was pushing a cart & just started talking to Saroo quite randomly. No spoon. No café. 
63
00:34:40,000 --> 00:34:51,000
FALSE
Saroo never met a man in a café. 
64
00:34:51,000 --> 00:35:24,000
TRUE-ISH
Saroo met a boy about his brother Guddu's age (15), who looked after him for a couple of days & then took him to the police. Once there, Saroo was unable to answer their questions. 
65
00:35:24,000 --> 00:35:29,000
FALSE-ISH
In reality, Saroo was locked in a cell overnight, then taken to a building where "official-looking people" asked questions, filled in forms & declared him lost. His first photograph was taken a month later by the adoption agency. (Also, the date is wrong. It was April 21st.)
66
00:35:29,000 --> 00:36:24,000
TRUE
Saroo was taken to a children's home & may have been given a haircut although it seems unlikely. The place was pretty brutal — much more so than is portrayed in the film. 
67
00:36:24,000 --> 00:36:51,000
TRUE
Pretty much, but in reality, the dorms were much more packed & from the description in the book, it's unlikely Saroo ever had a bed of his own (or a clean white vest). 
68
00:36:51,000 --> 00:37:27,000
FALSE
Saroo doesn't mention any friends at Liluah (the juveline detention centre in question). Rather he mentions bullying & beatings from both children & staff. 
69
00:37:27,000 --> 00:37:41,000
TRUE
Although the classroom part may not be true, Saroo writes that the centre was basically a dumping ground for mentally ill & disabled kids, as well as criminals, gang members & lost kids. A kid banging his head is very believable. 
70
00:37:41,000 --> 00:38:04,000
TRUE-ISH
Although Saroo doesn't write about this exact incident, it seems likely he saw similar things. 
71
00:38:04,000 --> 00:38:48,000
TRUE-ISH
All of the scenes in the detention centre are specific stories made up by the scriptwriter to convey the non-specific details conveyed in the book. There were, however, kids "acting crazily" & kids being abused. 
72
00:38:48,000 --> 00:39:52,000
FALSE
Saroo makes no mention of a tender dead-of-night singalong & it doesn't seem likely in the kind of place he describes. 
73
00:39:52,000 --> 00:40:11,000
TRUE
After a few weeks in Liluah, Saroo was moved to a much less brutal place, a pre-adoption orphanage called Nava Jeevan, where he met Mrs Sood. 
74
00:40:11,000 --> 00:41:19,000
TRUE
ISSA, the adoption agency, published a photo of Saroo in two newspapers in June 1987, but recieved no response. Mrs Sood did explain this to Saroo. 
75
00:41:19,000 --> 00:42:09,000
TRUE
This is near enough what happened, although it happened in a different place. 
76
00:42:09,000 --> 00:42:48,000
TRUE
Saroo was actually given a "bewitching little red photograph album" rather than a single photo, & he writes of accepting that he wouldn't see his family again at this point surprisingly readily. 
77
00:42:48,000 --> 00:42:54,000
FALSE-ISH
He writes of accepting that he wouldn't see his family again at this point surprisingly readily. 
78
00:42:54,000 --> 00:43:44,000
TRUE-ISH
Saroo met a little girl in pre-adoption place on whom Amita is probably based. She was called Asra & was also up for adoption in Australia. Saroo & Asra shared some poignant moments preparing for their new lives. 
79
00:43:44,000 --> 00:44:36,000
TRUE-ISH
The pre-adoption kids were taken to a nice house where a woman they were told to address as "Aunty Ula" taught them basic table manners but no English. Saroo writes: "I think I was taught to say 'Hello', but there was no time for more than that."
80
00:44:36,000 --> 00:45:33,000
TRUE
There were actually 4 adoption officials & 8 kids in total but let's not split hairs. He did fly to Australia in a Tasmania T-shirt, which had been sent to the adoption agency by the Brierleys. 
81
00:45:33,000 --> 00:46:32,000
TRUE-ISH
All of this happened as it did in the film, except there were 8 kids & various families & it happened in Melbourne. They had to take another flight to Hobart, but that was obviously deemed unnecessarily complicated for a cinema audience. 
82
00:46:32,000 --> 00:47:00,000
TRUE
They actually stayed in a hotel in Melbourne for a night, then flew to Hobart, before driving home, but it did happen. 
83
00:47:00,000 --> 00:48:03,000
TRUE
Saroo doesn't mention this happening exactly, but frankly, it must have happened on his first day in a new home so different to everything else he had known. 
84
00:48:03,000 --> 00:48:39,000
FALSE
This refers back to the English lessons he never had at the orphanage that wasn't portrayed in the film. As such, it can't be said to have happened.
85
00:48:39,000 --> 00:49:30,000
TRUE
Again, although this isn't mentioned in the book, it seems only fair to surmise that scenes very close to this must have taken place. 
86
00:49:30,000 --> 00:49:50,000
TRUE
Saroo writes of being taken out on the family catamaran often. 
87
00:49:50,000 --> 00:50:23,000
TRUE
Saroo writes of having a very active outdoor life with his adoptive parents & he speaks of playing cricket at other times, both in India & Australia.
88
00:50:23,000 --> 00:50:39,000
TRUE-ISH
Saroo was 10 by the time Mantosh arrived, so it was much longer than the "one year later" implied in the film. There is also no mention of the picture Saroo drew, but it seems reasonable that he will have drawn one. 
89
00:50:39,000 --> 00:51:11,000
TRUE
Although Saroo doesn't write about meeting Mantosh at the airport, we know that Mantosh was affected by some horrific experiences, so this scene rings perfectly true. 
90
00:51:11,000 --> 00:51:23,000
This is not known but seems reasonable. 
Again, this isn't mentioned in the book, but it seems perfectly reasonable. 
91
00:51:23,000 --> 00:51:50,000
TRUE
Mantosh frequently acted out physically & had to be restrained. 
92
00:51:50,000 --> 00:52:31,000
TRUE
This scene is not specifically recounted in the book but again, it must have happened. Saroo speaks of receiving much less attention once Mantosh arrived. 
93
00:52:31,000 --> 00:53:26,000
It may have happened. 
There is no mention of this in the book but it would be churlish to insist that it never happened, or indeed that it did. 
94
00:53:26,000 --> 00:53:59,000
TRUE
Saroo grew up loving the water. He even loved it in India, before he could swim, which resulted in a couple of near-drownings in Calcutta. 
95
00:53:59,000 --> 00:55:24,000
FALSE-ISH
Aside from the fact that Saroo went to Canberra rather than Melbourne, he makes no mention of Mantosh missing a goodbye lunch. It seems likely, however, that a goodbye lunch did take place. 
96
00:55:24,000 --> 00:56:46,000
May have happened, but is not recorded. 
Although there may well have been occasions such as this one, Saroo makes no mention of them, neither just before leaving to study, nor indeed ever. 
97
00:56:46,000 --> 00:57:02,000
TRUE-ISH
He actually went to study hospitality in Canberra. 
98
00:57:02,000 --> 00:57:30,000
FALSE
Lucy, you will be sad to hear, is a totally fictitious love interest that scriptwriters apparently insist on. Saroo mentions having girlfriends, but none during the 18 months he spent in Canberra. We feel betrayed. 
99
00:57:30,000 --> 00:58:05,000
FALSE-ISH
Saroo doesn't dwell on his studies in Canberra, but we can assume that there was an introductory seminar at some point. But Lucy wasn't there. 
100
00:58:05,000 --> 00:58:24,000
TRUE-ISH
Although not specifically referenced, Saroo writes about studying with many international students of Indian origin, a fact that brought his ethnicity to the forefront & saw him talking about his past like never before. 
101
00:58:24,000 --> 00:58:38,000
FALSE
Saroo didn't really care for Lucy at all, mostly on account of her not existing. 
102
00:58:38,000 --> 00:59:16,000
FALSE
This is one of the few scenes in the film that actually rings as false as it is. It also seems like a pale imitation of the Spike Jonze short film "How They Get There".
103
00:59:16,000 --> 00:59:32,000
FALSE 
There was no Saroo & Lucy. This relationship is not true. 
104
00:59:32,000 --> 01:00:04,000
TRUE
Although this particular party seems to be an imagined gathering, Saroo had a large social circle of Indian friends & became immersed in Indian culture as a result. 
105
01:00:04,000 --> 01:00:23,000
FALSE
Something similar may have happened as Saroo became immersed in Indian culture for the first time, but his Mum & Dad saw that he & Mantosh ate a lot of Indian food growing up, so maybe not. 
106
01:00:23,000 --> 01:01:12,000
FALSE
This is a beautiful scene full of swirling Proustian sensuousness as Saroo's past is conjured up by this heartbreaking sweetmeat. Sadly, it never happened. There is not a single mention of jalebis in the source material. 
107
01:01:12,000 --> 01:01:43,000
FALSE
None of this happened. Not only was Lucy not real, but the real Saroo didn't seem to have the profound melancholia bubbling under the surface that is suggested in this scene. 
108
01:01:43,000 --> 01:02:57,000
FALSE-ISH
Saroo says simply that he became aware of Google Earth after moving to Canberra & beginning to think about finding his home. There must have been a first time he heard it mentioned, but if this scene had occurred in real life, he would surely have written about it. 
109
01:02:57,000 --> 01:03:23,000
FALSE
In his own account, Saroo writes about being able to talk about his past freely for the first time & enjoying being able to talk to people who knew India & might be able to help. 
110
01:03:23,000 --> 01:04:02,000
FALSE
A little character development for a made-up character, but sadly, Lucy's mother is as fictitious as Lucy. 
111
01:04:02,000 --> 01:04:25,000
FALSE 
If Lucy had been real & had really asked him this question, it seems unlikely he would have been so unwilling to talk about it. But she wasn't. & she didn't. 
112
01:04:25,000 --> 01:05:00,000
FALSE
Not only is Lucy not real, but there is no mention of the mango scene in the book either. Pffft. 
113
01:05:00,000 --> 01:06:55,000
TRUE-ISH
There will have been the first time he checked Google Earth & began his search, but Lucy wasn't there & he probably wasn't so miserable about it. Also, his first search was centred on two half-remembered place names rather than train speeds & search radii. 
114
01:06:55,000 --> 01:07:03,000
TRUE-ISH
Although Saroo was back in Hobart by 2010, he actually moved back in 2009.
115
01:07:03,000 --> 01:07:42,000
FALSE
Saroo was aware of the enormity of his task & also aware that he had to concentrate on his studies, which he did, frequently forgetting about his search for months at a time. 
116
01:07:42,000 --> 01:09:03,000
FALSE
Saroo doesn't write about going up a mountain with any girlfriend, let alone a non-existent one. 
117
01:09:03,000 --> 01:10:41,000
TRUE-ISH
There is nothing in the book to suggest that this scene ever took place. Plus, let's not forget, Lucy wasn't real. However, it is true that Saroo kept his internet searching from his parents, not wanting to upset or worry them.
118
01:10:41,000 --> 01:12:39,000
FALSE
Saroo doesn't even hint at anything like this happening. Sadly, it smacks of sensationalism. Or if you prefer, filmmaking.
119
01:12:39,000 --> 01:13:04,000
FALSE
Something similar may have happened, but it's not based on events that Saroo chose to write about. 
120
01:13:04,000 --> 01:13:38,000
FALSE-ISH
The main problem with these scenes is that even when Saroo became properly obsessed, much much later back in Tasmania, it was a much more positive thing, an intellectual process of elimination rather than the lugubrious near-depression depicted in the film. 
121
01:13:38,000 --> 01:15:03,000
FALSE
No, none of this happened. He wouldn't get obsessed for years yet, & even when he did, & even when he lived with a woman called Lisa (on whom Lucy must be partly based) he reports no destructive aloofness. 
122
01:15:03,000 --> 01:15:58,000
FALSE
All of this feels like the filmmakers are over-soap-operafying his life. 
123
01:15:58,000 --> 01:16:15,000
FALSE
There is no suggestion that Saroo's attitude toward his past was a destructive force in his relationships — certainly not in such an overt way as portrayed in these scenes. 
124
01:16:15,000 --> 01:18:02,000
FALSE-ISH
None of this quite rings true and it certainly didn't happen in these circumstances. Neither does Saroo mention the wall maps looking like this, which he would have, if they did. 
125
01:18:02,000 --> 01:18:23,000
TRUE
Saroo talks about this happening the first time, realising then that it was bound to happen a lot as he continued to search. 
126
01:18:23,000 --> 01:19:11,000
FALSE-ISH
He talks about disheartening moments, but in reality, he didn't allow his search to overwhelm him or make him depressed. Rather, he talks about never forgetting his past, but never feeling that there was something missing, & never feeling that he couldn't enjoy his life. 
127
01:19:11,000 --> 01:19:54,000
FALSE
This scene feels very made up & seems to exist just to ramp up Saroo's misery, which is not really real. It seems very unlikely also that he would be such a dick as to leave his dad outside talking to him through the door. 
128
01:19:54,000 --> 01:20:01,000
FALSE
Having returned to Hobart, Saroo actually started working with his dad, something he really enjoyed & continued to do at least until the book was written. 
129
01:20:01,000 --> 01:20:39,000
FALSE 
Having Lucy as a constant, from college days right through to when the search became an obsession, is a choice the filmmakers made, but life isn't like that. Or at least wasn't, in this particular case. 
130
01:20:39,000 --> 01:21:22,000
TRUE-ISH
Saroo had these conversations years later with the woman who would become his long-term partner, Lisa. 
131
01:21:22,000 --> 01:22:20,000
FALSE 
A little more background for a woman that wasn't real. 
132
01:22:20,000 --> 01:22:36,000
TRUE
Saroo was hit by a motorbike whilst being paid by a market-seller to ferry watermelons across the street. 
133
01:22:36,000 --> 01:22:45,000
TRUE-ISH
In reality, the motorbike rider took pity on saroo & gave him a lift home. 
134
01:22:45,000 --> 01:23:00,000
FALSE 
This is just to consolidate the scar thing, which pops up again later. 
135
01:23:00,000 --> 01:23:49,000
TRUE
This was a conversation he had with his partner Lisa, after they had moved in together in 2010. 
136
01:23:49,000 --> 01:24:22,000
FALSE-ISH
When Saroo returned home after the accident, he says his mother took him straight to a doctor, who bandaged his injuries. 
137
01:24:22,000 --> 01:24:32,000
TRUE
Saroo spent a lot of time remembering his past, particularly as his obsession properly kicked in. 
138
01:24:32,000 --> 01:25:10,000
